---
/**
 * "Superdense coding" — v3 Phase 3 essay.
 *
 * The mirror of teleportation. Teleportation spent two classical
 * bits plus one shared Bell pair to move one qubit; superdense
 * spends one qubit plus one shared Bell pair to move two classical
 * bits. Same currency (entanglement), opposite direction.
 *
 * Two halves under one scroll, identical rhythm to /teleportation:
 *
 *   1. Algorithm half (ALG-03):
 *      - MultiBlochPanel (2 qubits, shared store) — q0=Alice,
 *        q1=Bob. Step through the protocol and both reduced Bloch
 *        arrows shrink to the origin (the Bell pair) and then snap
 *        back to a unique computational-basis outcome (Bob's decode).
 *      - ProtocolStepper (5 steps) drives the same store on the
 *        locked default `bits = "11"` walkthrough.
 *      - CircuitView shows the full 2-qubit circuit with the built-in
 *        "Copy as Qiskit" button from Phase 1.
 *      - SandboxLink remixes the same circuit.
 *
 *   2. Use-case half (USE-02):
 *      - EncodingTable — clickable 2×2 grid over `00 / 01 / 10 / 11`.
 *        Each row replays the matching superdense protocol into the
 *        same shared store, so the MultiBlochPanel above repaints in
 *        lockstep. Bob's decoded readout updates inline.
 *      - HolevoBound — slider over n = 1..4 transmitted qubits with
 *        side-by-side readouts of n (no-entanglement) vs 2n (super-
 *        dense). Closes the "doesn't this break information limits?"
 *        misconception in one interactive moment.
 *
 * Single source of truth: every circuit, step list, and encoding map
 * comes from `src/lib/quantum/superdense.ts`. Tests in
 * `tests/quantum/superdense.test.ts` pin the round-trip property the
 * page silently relies on (Bob decodes exactly the bits Alice picked).
 *
 * Convention: qubit register is `|q1 q0⟩` (Qiskit / LSB-first).
 *   q0 = Alice's qubit — the one she encodes onto and "sends".
 *   q1 = Bob's half of the pre-shared Bell pair.
 */
import EssayLayout from "../layouts/EssayLayout.astro";
import MathBlock from "../components/MathBlock.astro";
import MathNerds from "../components/MathNerds.astro";
import MultiBlochPanel from "../components/MultiBlochPanel.astro";
import ProtocolStepper from "../components/ProtocolStepper.astro";
import CircuitView from "../components/CircuitView.astro";
import EncodingTable from "../components/EncodingTable.astro";
import HolevoBound from "../components/HolevoBound.astro";
import SandboxLink from "../components/SandboxLink.astro";
import {
  superdenseCircuit,
  superdenseSteps,
} from "../lib/quantum";

const KEY = "superdense-essay";

/** Default to the locked `"11"` pedagogical demo so the static
 *  (no-JS) snapshot of CircuitView, ProtocolStepper, EncodingTable,
 *  and SandboxLink all show the same encoding — readers who land
 *  with JS disabled still see one consistent worked example. */
const circuit = superdenseCircuit("11");
const steps = superdenseSteps("11");
---

<EssayLayout
  title="Superdense coding"
  subtitle="Teleportation moved one qubit with two classical bits. Superdense moves two classical bits with one qubit. Same currency — a pre-shared Bell pair — running in the opposite direction. Then meet Holevo's bound, the ceiling that says you can't do better than 2x."
  description="Walk Alice → Bob superdense coding step by step: prepare the shared Bell pair, encode two classical bits with one of four single-qubit gates (I, X, Z, XZ), send one qubit, decode with the Bell-basis inverse. Compare the 2x classical-capacity gain against Holevo's bound — the ceiling no quantum protocol beats."
>
  <p>
    The <a href="/teleportation">previous essay</a> spent two
    classical bits plus a pre-shared Bell pair to move one qubit of
    quantum information from Alice to Bob. This essay is the mirror.
    Alice has two classical bits she wants to send to Bob. They also
    share a pre-shared Bell pair (set up in the same lab beforehand,
    then carried apart). Alice applies one of four single-qubit
    gates to her half of the pair, sends that single qubit over a
    quantum channel, and Bob runs a short decode that reads off both
    classical bits. One qubit transmitted, two classical bits
    received. The Bell pair did the rest.
  </p>

  <p>
    That sounds like it should break some kind of information limit
    — and the second half of this essay is the careful look that
    says: no, it doesn't. Pre-shared entanglement doubles classical
    capacity from <code>n</code> bits per <code>n</code> qubits to
    <code>2n</code>, and that's it. <strong>Holevo's bound</strong>
    is the ceiling. Superdense meets it; nothing beats it.
  </p>

  <h2>The two qubits</h2>

  <p data-step="0">
    Two qubits, same index convention as the rest of the codebase —
    <code>|q<sub>1</sub> q<sub>0</sub>⟩</code>, LSB-first,
    Qiskit-compatible:
  </p>

  <ul class="my-4 font-mono text-sm text-ink-muted">
    <li>q<sub>0</sub> — Alice's qubit. She encodes the two classical bits onto it, then ships it to Bob.</li>
    <li>q<sub>1</sub> — Bob's half of the pre-shared Bell pair.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Alice can touch q<sub>0</sub>. Bob can touch q<sub>1</sub>, and
    once Alice sends, he can touch q<sub>0</sub> too. The Bell pair
    is established <em>before</em> Alice decides what to send; it's
    a resource sitting in both labs, waiting. Nothing magical
    happens at encode time — Alice's gate is local, on a qubit she
    already has — yet the act of choosing which of four gates to
    apply rotates the joint two-qubit state into one of the four
    mutually-orthogonal Bell states. That's the trick the rest of
    this essay unpacks.
  </p>

  <h2>Step through the protocol</h2>

  <p data-step="1">
    The widget below shows two live Bloch cards
    (q<sub>0</sub>, q<sub>1</sub>), each rendering that qubit's
    reduced state. Below them, a stepper walks the five-step
    protocol on the locked default encoding <code>bits = "11"</code>
    (Alice applies <code>XZ</code>). Each transition updates the
    shared two-qubit simulator under the hood and the cards repaint
    to match. Step backward and forward freely — the stepper replays
    from scratch each time, so jumps never drift.
  </p>

  <MultiBlochPanel
    storeKey={KEY}
    qubits={2}
    captions={[
      "q₀ — Alice (encodes XZ)",
      "q₁ — Bob",
    ]}
    caption="Per-qubit reduced Bloch arrows. Watch both arrows shrink to the origin once the Bell pair is built; Alice's encoding rotates the joint state without changing either reduced arrow; Bob's decode snaps both arrows back to the unique computational outcome 11."
  />

  <ProtocolStepper
    storeKey={KEY}
    qubits={2}
    steps={steps}
    caption="Step through Alice's encoding of bits = 11 and Bob's Bell-basis decode."
  />

  <p data-step="2">
    <strong>Try this:</strong> press <em>Next</em> through all five
    steps. The cascade you should see:
  </p>

  <ol class="my-4 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      <strong>Prepare the shared Bell pair on (q<sub>0</sub>, q<sub>1</sub>).</strong>
      <code>H</code> on q<sub>0</sub> then <code>CNOT(q<sub>0</sub> → q<sub>1</sub>)</code>
      builds <code>|Φ+⟩ = (|00⟩ + |11⟩) / √2</code>. Both reduced
      arrows shrink to the origin and the "Entangled" badge lights
      up on both cards.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Alice encodes <code>11</code> with <code>XZ</code>.</strong>
      A single-qubit operation on q<sub>0</sub> only. The joint
      state rotates from <code>|Φ+⟩</code> to <code>|Ψ-⟩</code> —
      one of the four mutually orthogonal Bell states. From either
      reduced-state point of view nothing changed; the joint state
      is now in a different Bell basis vector entirely.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Alice sends q<sub>0</sub> to Bob.</strong> Physically
      one qubit travels the wire. The state vector doesn't change —
      this step is narrative — but it's the only step where
      anything actually moves through space.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Bob decodes with <code>CNOT(q<sub>0</sub> → q<sub>1</sub>)</code>.</strong>
      First half of the inverse of the Bell-pair prep. The bit-flip
      half of Alice's encoding gets untangled into q<sub>1</sub>'s
      computational amplitude.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Bob decodes with <code>H</code> on q<sub>0</sub> and reads the result.</strong>
      Hadamard finishes the Bell-basis inverse. Both reduced
      arrows snap to the south pole — the joint state is
      <code>|11⟩</code>. Bob measures <code>(q<sub>1</sub>, q<sub>0</sub>) = (1, 1)</code>.
      Exactly the two bits Alice picked.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The full circuit</h2>

  <p data-step="3">
    The circuit below is everything the simulator runs. The first
    two columns are the Bell-pair prep; the third column is Alice's
    encoding (here <code>X</code> followed by <code>Z</code> for
    <code>bits = "11"</code>); the next two columns are Bob's
    decode — the literal inverse of the prep. The trailing two
    measurements turn the resulting computational-basis amplitudes
    into the two bits Bob reads. "Copy as Qiskit" emits a Python
    snippet you can paste straight into a notebook.
  </p>

  <CircuitView
    circuit={circuit}
    caption="Superdense coding (2 qubits, bits = 11). Columns 1–2 = Bell-pair prep H · CNOT; column 3–4 = Alice's encoding X then Z; columns 5–6 = Bob's decode CNOT then H; columns 7–8 = the readout measurements."
  />

  <p class="my-6">
    <SandboxLink circuit={circuit} label="Remix in sandbox →" />
  </p>

  <h2>The four encodings</h2>

  <p data-step="4">
    Alice has four choices. The mapping is locked: each pair of
    bits picks one of <code>{`{ I, X, Z, XZ }`}</code> on
    q<sub>0</sub>, and that gate rotates the joint Bell state into
    one of the four orthogonal Bell states. Click any row to replay
    that encoding into the shared store — the Bloch panel above
    repaints to match, and Bob's decoded readout (which is
    deterministic, courtesy of <code>decodeSuperdense</code> in
    the simulator) updates inline.
  </p>

  <EncodingTable
    storeKey={KEY}
    initialBits="11"
    caption="Click a row to encode the two classical bits on Alice's qubit. Bob's decoded bits are computed live from the simulator — they always match the input."
  />

  <p>
    The bit-pair → gate → Bell-state map is the heart of the
    protocol. It's the same map every textbook prints and the same
    map the simulator runs; the round-trip property "the bits Bob
    reads equal the bits Alice picked" is pinned by the test suite
    so a regression would break CI before reaching this page.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this isn't a free-bandwidth tap</h2>

  <p data-step="5">
    Two classical bits delivered by transmitting one qubit looks
    like a 2x bandwidth multiplier. It is — but only because the
    pre-shared Bell pair was already in Bob's lab. The Bell pair
    had to be created somewhere and carried (or beamed) to Bob
    once, before any encoding could happen. That transit doesn't
    show up in the "bits per channel use" figure of merit, which
    is why superdense looks like a free-bandwidth tap and isn't.
  </p>

  <p>
    More importantly, you can't do better. <strong>Holevo's bound</strong>
    is a hard ceiling: no quantum protocol — superdense, anything
    cleverer that anyone has ever invented, anything cleverer than
    anyone <em>will</em> invent — transmits more than <code>2n</code>
    classical bits through <code>n</code> qubits of channel use,
    even with unlimited entanglement set up in advance. Superdense
    is the protocol that meets the ceiling. The slider below lets
    you watch the two lines diverge at the locked 2x ratio:
  </p>

  <HolevoBound
    initialN={1}
    caption="No-entanglement classical capacity is n; superdense capacity with a pre-shared Bell pair is 2n. The gap is the entanglement advantage — capped at 2x by Holevo's bound."
  />

  <p>
    The proof of the bound is not trivial — it's an information-
    theoretic argument about the maximum mutual information
    between a classical message ensemble and the quantum states
    that encode it. The bound itself,
    <code>I(X:Y) ≤ S(ρ) − Σ p<sub>i</sub> S(ρ<sub>i</sub>)</code>,
    is named for Alexander Holevo and was settled in 1973. The
    upshot for an engineer pricing out bandwidth is the same as
    the upshot for an engineer pricing out a teleportation link:
    entanglement is a finite resource that costs something to
    establish, and once you have it, it doubles classical capacity
    in one direction or moves one qubit in the other. Pick which
    way you want to spend it.
  </p>

  <h2>Self-test</h2>

  <ol class="my-6 list-decimal space-y-3 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      Click each of the four rows in the encoding table in turn and
      watch the Bloch panel above. Why do the two reduced arrows
      stay at the origin through Alice's encoding step — even
      though the joint state visibly changes Bell-state identity?
      (Hint: each qubit's reduced density matrix is <code>I / 2</code>
      for every Bell state. Tracing out one half of any Bell state
      gives the maximally mixed state on the other.)
    </li>
    <li>
      Drag the Holevo slider to <code>n = 4</code>. The superdense
      readout says "at most 8 classical bits." Could you build a
      protocol that beats that — say, by chaining two Bell pairs
      cleverly? (Answer: no. The bound is on the total. Two Bell
      pairs let you superdense-encode 4 bits through 2 qubits, not
      more.)
    </li>
  </ol>

  <MathNerds title="The Bell basis, the four encodings, and why the decode works">
    <p>
      The four Bell states are the orthonormal basis of the
      two-qubit Hilbert space favored by every entanglement-aware
      protocol:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="|\Phi^+\rangle = \tfrac{1}{\sqrt 2}(|00\rangle + |11\rangle), \quad |\Psi^+\rangle = \tfrac{1}{\sqrt 2}(|01\rangle + |10\rangle)" />
    <MathBlock tex="|\Phi^-\rangle = \tfrac{1}{\sqrt 2}(|00\rangle - |11\rangle), \quad |\Psi^-\rangle = \tfrac{1}{\sqrt 2}(|01\rangle - |10\rangle)" />
    <p>
      The Bell-pair prep <code>(H ⊗ I) · CNOT(q<sub>0</sub> → q<sub>1</sub>)</code>
      — read right to left — maps <code>|00⟩ → |Φ+⟩</code>. Each
      Pauli applied to <em>just</em> q<sub>0</sub> moves the joint
      state to a different Bell state:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="(I \otimes I)|\Phi^+\rangle = |\Phi^+\rangle, \quad (X \otimes I)|\Phi^+\rangle = |\Psi^+\rangle" />
    <MathBlock tex="(Z \otimes I)|\Phi^+\rangle = |\Phi^-\rangle, \quad (XZ \otimes I)|\Phi^+\rangle = |\Psi^-\rangle" />
    <p>
      Each is a single, purely local operation on Alice's qubit.
      That's the encoding map: <code>bits</code> picks one of
      <code>{`{ I, X, Z, XZ }`}</code>, and the joint state rotates
      to the corresponding Bell vector. Notably,
      <code>XZ ≠ ZX</code> as gates (they differ by a global phase),
      but <code>(XZ ⊗ I)|Φ+⟩ = (ZX ⊗ I)|Φ+⟩</code> up to that
      same global phase — so the locked table uses
      <code>XZ</code> consistently and the math underneath is the
      same on both sides.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bob's decode is the inverse of the prep:
      <code>(H ⊗ I) · CNOT(q<sub>0</sub> → q<sub>1</sub>)</code>
      again (a self-inverse on each piece because <code>H · H = I</code>
      and <code>CNOT · CNOT = I</code>). Applied to each Bell
      state, the decode produces the computational basis vector
      whose two bits are exactly the bits Alice picked — that's
      the round-trip property the encoding table relies on, and
      it's what makes the protocol "deterministic" rather than
      "high-probability."
    </p>
    <p>
      The information-theoretic ceiling above is Holevo (1973):
      for an ensemble <code>{`{ p_i, ρ_i }`}</code> encoding the
      classical message <code>X</code> as the quantum state
      <code>Y</code>,
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="I(X:Y) \;\leq\; S\!\bigl(\textstyle\sum_i p_i\, \rho_i\bigr) - \sum_i p_i\, S(\rho_i)" />
    <p>
      with <code>S</code> the von Neumann entropy. The right-hand
      side is maximized at <code>log₂(d) = n</code> bits for
      <code>n</code> qubits without auxiliary entanglement, and at
      <code>2n</code> bits with a pre-shared Bell pair. Superdense
      attains the second; that's why the chart's superdense line
      sits on the 2n ceiling and the no-entanglement line sits on
      the n ceiling. Nothing in between, nothing above.
    </p>
  </MathNerds>

  <Fragment slot="footer-nav">
    <a href="/teleportation" class="hover:text-ink">← Teleportation</a>
    <a href="/grover" class="hover:text-ink">Next: Grover →</a>
  </Fragment>
</EssayLayout>

<script>
  import { attachScrolly } from "../lib/scrolly";
  import { mountAnnotations } from "../lib/annotations";

  const root = document.querySelector("article");
  if (root) {
    attachScrolly(root, {
      stepSelector: "[data-step]",
      onStep: (i) => console.debug(`[scrolly] step ${i}`),
    });
  }

  const ann = mountAnnotations();
  document.getElementById("reset-annotations")?.addEventListener("click", () => {
    ann.reset();
  });

  // No inline gate buttons on this essay — ProtocolStepper, EncodingTable,
  // and HolevoBound each mount themselves on DOMContentLoaded. The
  // shared store (`KEY`) is created by whichever sibling widget hydrates
  // first; `ensureStore` is idempotent by key, so the order doesn't matter.
</script>
